Oct 1 2009 	The Tank Isn't Worth It	My husband and I stayed here this past weekend. We were traveling with another couple and at time of reservation (online) we both made note that we were traveling together and would like to stay near each other. We checked in at different times, however, since we were flying from different cities, and that request must have been too much because we were nowhere near each other (same tower, different elevators--6th floor versus 14th floor). However, not a big deal and we didn't mention it to the staff.The room was very comfortable and good sized. There was some residual hallway noise but nothing that kept us up. However, there did appear to be a wrestling match occurring on the floor above ours at 3AM that lasted a couple of hours before the occupants were, presumably, thrown out. We didn't complain to the staff though since I had no problem sleeping through it and my husband doesn't typically complain about things once the matter has been resolved. Our view was not attractive, though we could see portions of the pool and Fremont Street Experience. The bathroom was nice and the complimentary lotions, etc. were VERY nice.The hotel itself was nice. It felt very new and clean, not dated or old. It did take a while to get from the room to the outdoors, but definitely not as long as it does at a hotel on The Strip. Probably just about 5-10 minutes (versus 20+ on The Strip). The timeshare sales staff stationed outside the South Tower elevators didn't bother us at all. I wish they were all like that. We dined at the Cafe, the H2O bar, and Lillie's Noodle House. All had good food and good service. The H2O bar, perhaps expectedly, was pretty expensive, though ($17 for 2 tequila sunrises, $20 for five Bud Lights).The Tank was awesome and the only reason we chose to stay at the Golden Nugget. It is a little small, both the pool and the seating area, especially for the crowd, but we found seats every day and enjoyed ourselves immensely. The slide didn't get crowded at all and we were able to ride it whenever we wanted. Although the pool was nice, and the hotel itself was nice, I wouldn't stay there again. The downtown area has a different vibe from The Strip, more &quot;down and out&quot; than &quot;What Happens in Vegas,&quot; probably due to the downtown area being primarily frequented by locals rather than tourists. Plus, with no cheap and easy way to get to The Strip (one way bus fare is $3, $7 for 24 hour pass), and not enough to entertain oneself for a full weekend, it would make more sense to stay on The Strip and visit the downtown area than vice versa.	
