Sep 13 2009 	Vintage Vegas -- excellent value for money and fab pool!	Let me preface by saying I've stayed at the Bellagio and the Palazzo (both of which had gorgeous rooms) and I was very hesitant to stay here. But I decided to take a risk and I'm glad I did. We stayed on the 22nd floor of the South Tower in a room supposedly remodeled in 2009 and we paid $49 for the first night (a Thursday) and $159 for the second night (Friday). The Good:Excellent value for money, esp. at the $49 rate. If both nights were $159, I would not have stayed here because I got the same rate at Bellagio but I wanted to save some bucks and spend it on a great dinner out. The room was large and clean but the furniture looked dated and a little scuffed. The bathroom is tiny and the door opens inward which makes it even more crowded. The sink is ridiculously small. However, it's serviceable. All amenities provided, flat screen TV, blow dryer, lotion, shampoo, iron and board, etc. and replenished each day. I was surprised to see robes hanging in our closet. That is a luxury hotel amenity and to find it in a $49 room is pretty amazing. The pool is fantastic! If you have kids, I can't think of a better way to have them spend the day than under the waterfalls and hurtling down the water slide that cuts through the shark tank. Yes, there are live sharks swimming in the shark tank and you can gaze at them while they peer at you through the glass. You can do the water slide and lie out on the lounges to your heart's content and never have to spend a dime unless you want to buy beer and food, which is always a good idea. The weekday crowd seems to be working-class families, the weekend crowd seems to trend younger with lots of L.A. and O.C. visitors. The steakhouse at the hotel is pretty good and I have reviewed it separately on yelp.com.Lots of slot machines (which I don't use) and gaming tables of all kinds. I played texas hold-em at the lowest limit table ($2/$4) and the dealers were helpful and friendly and most of the players were nice. The Bad:Most of the staff don't look particularly happy and aren't particularly pleasant. We did end up getting upgraded to the 22nd floor at check-in and a waiver of the $12.99/24hr. internet fee the next day but it was not easy to do. And none of the workers seem to smile much. Maybe they don't get paid well and that's why the hotel is good value for money? Hmmm. Not very convenient to the Strip so if you don't have a car, you'll have to take the City Bus or taxis if you want to get up where all the action is. We had no trouble driving and we also enjoyed exploring Fremont Street. If you're on a budget, things seem to be a little less expensive at that end of town anyway.Side Notes:You have to prance through the hotel lobby in your robe to get to the pool. I guess you have to do this most places but it felt strange.Lots of shiny gold and mirrors all around. No doubt this was high style back in the day but if you're looking for uber-chic Zen decor, this place isn't it. The casino in particular seems very poorly lit, and I'm not sure why. In sum, put on some vintage clothes and vintage attitude, let go of your expectations, and kick back for good times. And don't forget to swim with the sharks!	
