Sep 2 2009 	A Great Time!	It's been over 5 years since I stayed downtown at the Golden Nugget in Las Vegas and I certainly missed the experience. My wife and I decided to spend two evenings on the strip (Flamingo) and two evenings at the GN. We both agreed that the GN was a much better time. Valet and check in moved very quickly. The room, even in the South Tower, was very nice and spacious. I know some complain about the walk, but it just did not bother us. Seemed we had an even longer walk in the Flamingo. The casino floor and restaurants are great and you can't beat the location on Freemont Street which was such a blast on the weekend. The highlight for us was the pool area. We spend both of our afternoons there and really enjoyed ourselves. The shark tank is simply amazing and we found ourselves gazing into it for quite some time. Very much a party atmosphere on the weekend with alcohol everywhere and many people drinking in the pool itself. Unsure if the best place for kids on the weekend because of that. Sunday there was much more quiet with many kids splashing around. My only complaints (and really not a huge deal) was the elevators. They appeared to take some time to get to the main floor and for some reason kept playing the same video clip over and over again when you got on (Gordie Brown singing Ice Ice Baby)...after drinking that was the last tune I wanted to hear.But overall a great time and a good idea for a alternative to the expensive strip resorts.	
Sep 1 2009 	Best Downtown has to offer	We just returned from our second trip to Vegas this year. Stayed at the Nugget both times. We've tried all the other downtown hotels and none can compare to the Nugget for cleanliness and amenities. We always stay in the South Tower and have gotten great rooms that have been renovated with nice bed covers, flat screen TV and pillow top mattress. The rain shower head in the bath is not that great, no pressure. But it got the job done. The A/C was struggling during the day to cool the room but at night it was sufficient. It was only 111 degrees the day we left so any A/C unit is going to struggle. We have been staying Downtown Vegas since 1991 and will never stay on the Strip again. However, Downtown is getting too much like the Strip since they have covered Fremont St. Go during the week when the crowds are smaller. We love staying at the Nugget but don't gamble there because the slots are very tight. We ate the breakfast buffet but was disappointed at how it has gone downhill from a few years ago. Not as much variety and the food was dried out and tasteless. We didn't even try lunch or dinner. Ate elswhere. The other casinos have deteriorated so much that if you want to stay Downtown the Nugget is your best option. We will stay there again when we go next Spring.	
Sep 1 2009 	Beware - you do are not guaranteed the room type you reserved...	This was my 6th trip to Las Vegas, and my first time staying in the downtown area. The last time we were here, we went into the Golden Nugget casino and I decided that I wanted to stay there the next time we went. My boyfriend's birthday was last week, so I treated him to a weekend in Las Vegas for his birthday and one last blast before he had knee surgery (today).I made my reservations through the Golden Nugget, via the telephone. I told them I wanted a room with a king bed, and they said they would give me the special rates on the internet of $89.00/weekend night &amp; $49.00/weekday night. I was also supposed to get a $25.00 room and beverage credit. I guaranteed this all on my credit card.When we arrived around 10:00 p.m. on Saturday night (and I had informed the agent who took my reservation that we'd be arriving late) I was told that there were no more king bed rooms left, but that they could give us a room with 2 doubles. This did not make me happy as every other time I have traveled and guaranteed a room with a credit card, that means you get the room type you reserved. The desk clerk told me that they NEVER guarantee room types, which I thought odd since the reservation agent never mentioned that. I argued that I had never run across such a policy, but she kept on insisting that &quot;almost all&quot; hotels in Las Vegas had that policy. (Again, in my previous stays in Las Vegas, I always have been given the room type I had reserved.) The desk clerk told us that we could be &quot;put on a list for a room change the following day&quot; and would offer nothing more.We went up to our room and found that not only were the beds way too squishy and uncomfortable, but they were really short. My boyfriend and I are both fairly tall, and our legs were hanging over the edge. Not to mention that this was supposed to be a romantic birthday getaway for us, and now we were relegated to separate beds that could not be pushed together.I called the front desk again and explained that this room would not do. After putting me on a hold for a few minutes, the desk clerk came back and said that &quot;an unexpected check out&quot; occurred in a king room and that it was being cleaned and she could contact us in 20 minutes with the status. Fast forward to 30 minutes in the future, and we still hadn't heard from the front desk. I called down again, and was put on an endless hold. I hung up and called a second time (again on hold forever) and this time was told it would be another 15 minutes or so. While I was on the phone, another clerk left a message that we could either stay in the room or come down to the front desk to exchange keys (but of course, the room wasn't ready yet). We opted to go down to the front desk because by now about 45 minutes had elapsed, we hadn't eaten, and we were very unhappy with the way we were being treated.The front desk clerk we got this time checked on the status, made a call to whomever it was that we were dealing with before, and then announced that our room was ready. It apparently had been available all along, it was a &quot;set-aside&quot; room that they hold for either their friends or emergencies, and they put them in &quot;cleaning status&quot; to show them as unavailable in the computer. I never did get an explanation of why it took them nearly an hour to rectify this for us, just a lecture on how &quot;next time get the name of the reservation agent you spoke with&quot; on the phone. I also had to ask them to give us the $25.00 food &amp; beverage credit. There will not be a &quot;next time.&quot;	
Sep 1 2009 	Good value stay	Just returned from 3 nights at the Nuggett (after 3 at the Flamingo). This is the first time I have stayed Downtown. Have to say I was pleased with both the hotel and Fremont Street.The hotel itself is well run, clean and with good amenities. We stayed in the South Tower (ie. the non-refurbed rooms) and the rooms were still good. Didn't see any of the poor carpets or furnishings that others had seen. Nice flat screen TV, comfy beds (if a little soft) and robes provided.The pool area is lovely, though is indeed a little cramped. It opens at 8, but the pools are only staffed by 10. We tried both the Italian and steak restaurants. Both were good value.While Fremont Street is no Strip, it's a fun place for a couple of nights and doesn't have the extreme walks associated with the bigger hotels. The hotels surrounding the Nuggett are fairly cheap and cheerful, but the gambling is fair (plenty of $5 tables). I wouldn't choose to wander off the covered area of Fremont Street, which does look rather down at heel, but there is really little need for you to do so.Would definitely recommend if you are a repeat visitor, who has seen most of the Strip sights.	
Sep 1 2009 	Loved it.......	We stayed at the GN 8/28-8/31. We booked the hotel with my husband's air miles through his business card as the other hotels offered were on the strip and we had stayed at each of them. That said, I still did my research. Check-in was quick. We arrived around 3 or so and it took maybe 10 minutes, if that. We ended up in the South Tower, Room 2296. Nice big king bed, large flat screen, plenty of lamps for lighting. This was good as we did not have much of a view - but I don't spend much time staring out the window.The bathroom was nice sized - I certainly didn't have any trouble turning on the water, showerhead, etc. standing outside the tub, nor did I have to lay down to rinse my hair - the shower head had great pressure. The tub did drain rather slowly, however.Housekeeping was quite efficient. One phone call and pillows arrived not ten minutes later. They did the rooms twice a day - 8am and 3pm. If you didn't want to be bothered, you just put your privacy sign out.I am guessing that some of the other posters who thought the south tower was such a long walk have never stayed anywhere like Caesers, MGM or some of the other strip hotels. From the south tower elevators it was straight down the hall to the pool, a right then a left and a little more walking and there was the casino. Very convenient. Never did hear any street noise from our room - never even heard our neighbors or people in the hall.The pool area was great. For an FYI for those that are interested, if you are looking directly at the shark tank, the sun hits on the left side of the pool first in the am, then moves across to the right mid-day, and then back to the left late afternoon. Plenty of lounge chairs (with great pads) and seating areas with couches - chairs were plentiful until around 10am or so and then they got sparse. The are also two levels with cabanas above the pools and any chairs that are not in front of cabanas are open to all. Pool opens officially at 10am but you can get in around 830-900am and get a chair; just no towels or swimming until 10.Food was good - the Grotto has wonderful pizza. Cocktail waitressess are all over and you never really had a wait for a cocktail. I played craps and had a great time - even if I am a wussy bettor! Starts at a $5 minimum and at 8 or so goes to $10 but if you have been playing at the lower minimum you can stay at it.Only thing I was a little annoyed at was charging to my room - no problem several times and then at the gift shop all of the sudden they wanted my id! Suppossedly this is policy but then it should be enforced all across the hotel and they should tell you at check-in. Minor inconvenience but annoying.P.S. Thoes &quot;people&quot; outside the south elevators that want to give you &quot;gifts&quot;? They are time share hawkers - imho way more annoying than porn slappers!!	
