Aug 18 2009 	Fun Spa Tower Suite Stay	After seeing video of this suite on Expedia, I have always really wanted to stay here. The look of it just evoked fun old Vegas cheesy luxury to me! And our suite ended up looking exactly like the video, very nice. The spa tower suite is about 1200 sq feet, has two story windows, with views either overlooking the pool or Fremont Street. The room feels even more spacious because of the huge windows and two open floors. All the drapes work electronically, very cool. There's also a large bar area with a coffee maker and an empty fridge, a nice perk in Vegas. The upstairs bathroom is huge and has a steam shower and big, very comfortable whirlpool bath, a separate w/c with toilet and bidet, a vanity area, a tv over the sinks. There are even mirrors over the king bed, which I tried very hard to avoid looking up at !The room is very clean and well maintained; my only small quibble with the room is that there is an industrial type of brown carpet that covers the stairs and entire upstairs, including bathroom. Sorta detracts from the overall luxury feel the room's going for, but that's minor.Check in is in the Vip area, a nice touch; I found the desk clerk a bit cold, though polite. Would I stay in this room again? Probably, I do enjoy the strip more, but the GN is a good hotel, and the spa tower room is great for a special occasion if you find it for under $300 a night.	
Aug 18 2009 	Really Enjoyed Our Stay	We've been to Vegas many times, typically staying on the strip. A few things have gotten old about it - the litter, the crowds at night, and the bad gaming odds at strip casinos. We spent a night of our last trip at the Golden Nugget to give downtown a try. This time we spent all three nights (Fri-Sun) there. After this trip, we're sold on downtown. We had a south tower room, which was spotless, had a 42 inch flat-screen TV and a very comfortable king mattress. The hotel was full according to the desk clerk, but the soundproofing between rooms seemed very good. While we saw our neighbors in the hallway, we never heard them. Yes, the bathrooms are small by strip standards, but there is a make-up desk and mirror just outside the bathroom. The shower head was excellent (one of those &quot;rain&quot; types) and the towels plush. We didn't try the restaurants, but had the lunch buffet one day and breakfast buffet another. No buffet is gourmet, but the food selections and quality were more than adequate and the buffet dining room is pleasant.The pool is a big attraction, but is too small and crowded for actual swimming (it's best for just taking a dip and looking into the aquarium). We didn't have much difficulty finding a couple of lounge chairs. It only took a couple of minutes of &quot;cruising&quot; to find someone who was leaving. They chaises are close together, but very comfortable. Much of the area is shaded at times by the buildings, but to us that's a plus since it's still plenty hot and prevents sunburn. Every staff member we encountered in our stay was pleasant and helpful. We did pay the extra $20 for VIP check-in, which I think was worth it since it was a busy weekend and we wanted to be assured of getting the room type we requested and not having a long wait in line. We checked in about 10:00 Friday morning, and the two woman at the VIP desk gave us a room immediately without our having to ask if that was possible so early. When we checked out Monday there was a line at the main area, but we got helped immediately in the VIP room. I'd do it in the future if coming on a weekend. If anyone at the Golden Nugget reads these reviews, I do have one question - what are you going to do about the pool area when your new building opens? It may be genuinely overcrowded at that point. A plug for downtown in general - we were amazed by the almost total lack of trash compared to the strip. Even off of Fremont street in the neighboring blocks to the north, it was clear that street cleaning is a high priority. Also, there are none of those obnoxious people passing out the girly cards that are everywhere on the strip. Must be something different about city vs. Clark County (where the strip is) rules. Also, the entertainment downtown was outstanding. Major props to the downtown association or whoever it is that puts on the events. The Woodstock Tribute Weekend bands were all excellent. I think some might be better than the original bands they covered (&quot;Jimi Hendrix&quot;, &quot;Janis Joplin&quot;, and &quot;Joe Cocker&quot; were fantastic). The crowds were ample and the mood very festive. I was also surprised and pleased with demographic of the downtown crowd. I expected old and downbeat, but actually it was pretty much the same mix as the strip. Very few visible &quot;bums&quot; either. Throw in that the gaming odds are much better in most downtown hotels, food deals are still plentiful, and it's easy to walk around with the shade and width of Fremont Street. We thought we'd spend at least part of our visit going up to the strip, but we ended up only leaving downtown once. We're no longer into the nightclub scene, but I'd say that is one area where the strip holds a real edge. We'll look first to downtown and the Golden Nugget for our future stays.	
