Jul 24 2009 	Nice...real gamblers should ALWAYS stay Downtown not the Strip!	First off, if your primary reason for coming to Vegas is to gamble, it's foolish to stay anywhere BUT Downtown in the Fremont Street area. I want to be absolutely clear to anyone who is trying to decided between the Strip and Downtown. The big boys on the Strip have decided to fight the recession by gouging you at the tables. All of the hotel/casinos I visited that are part of Harrahs, and all of the the ones owned by MGM/Mirage DON'T OFFER REAL BLACKJACK AT A REAL PRICE! Take note of that. ALL of the blackjack tables on the Strip that I visited now only pay 6:5 on a blackjack hand, as opposed to the REAL blackjack, which SHOULD pay 3:2. This raises the house advantage pretty substantially. I'm hoping you won't be like the rest of the dopes at these casinos throwing their money away obliviously, thinking they're playing blackjack: they ain't. 'Nuff said!Now, as for the Golden Nugget...this was my first time staying there, having snagged a deal months beforehand on Continental Vacations. We usually stay next door at Four Queens. Usually the Four Queens is cheaper, but not this time. The Golden Nugget has a reputation of being the &quot;Wynn&quot; of Downtown. (The Nugget was Wynn's first casino.)The hotel was nice, but not really much nicer than the Four Queens. And it's much bigger, and the layout and distance from different areas will require your walking shoes. The room was old, but clean and well-kept. The televisions in the South Tower, where we stayed, were older; not really acceptable at this level. The beds were comfortable and the room was fairly large. Oddly, there is no mini-fridge, and housekeeping never gave us shower floor towels. The room, though, was quiet, service was good, and the A/C (so vitally important in this sauna of a climate) worked well.I am an avid runner, and wanted to use the workout facilities. The spa/workout room was nice, but it will cost you a &quot;nominal&quot; $20 to use them...per day. I hate that.Very cool pool area, with a circular pool and water slide that surrounds (and the slide goes through) a shark-infested aquarium. The bottom line is that the Golden Nugget is nice, but I personally wouldn't pay more for it if the Four Queens was cheaper, as it usually is. That said, Golden Nugget should please most people.	
