Jul 23 2009 	Golden Nugget – A pleasant surprise for our family vacation	We reserved rooms at the Golden Nugget to start our western family vacation, and were pleasantly surprised and very pleased with our stay.Our rooms were in the south tower, and were the lowest cost room type available when we booked. They were recently renovated, in very good condition, and included flat-panel LCD TV, an air conditioner that left our room well cooled on one of this summer’s hottest days, a low table at the entry with a make-up mirror, and two very comfortable beds. For business travelers, there is no desk or other adequate workspace, but there is cabled and wireless HSIA available at $12.99 per day. Owing to its status as an older hotel, the guest room bathrooms are well-appointed, but small.While the room rate was shown as $50 per night, when we called to make reservations, it quickly escalated to more than $75 once we told the reservationist that our seven year old child would be with us – and – we elected to pay an extra $20 charge in order to be able to skip long check-in and check-out lines and work through the VIP lounge instead. But, given the length of lines we saw when we arrived, it was $20 well spent.Food and beverage was good, too. The Casino Café served standard fare (steaks, burgers, sandwiches, pasta) and service was prompt. We didn’t try the other restaurants, but they were very busy and seemed fine.The treat for our family was the pool area and water slide/tube through the shark tank. The kids loved it, and made a dozen trips through the tube during our afternoon there. There is no cost for doing the shark tube slide, and even on a busy day, the maximum wait was about 10 minutes. The pool area itself is very small – grab a chair early if you plan to use it that day. The H2O bar area is nice, but not over the top.Another treat at the Golden Nugget is the pool-side Blackjack tables. For evening entertainment, the Fremont Experience outside the hotels in that section of downtown Las Vegas is cheesy but entertaining.Parking was free for hotel guests in a deck behind the rear of the hotel.Overall, we’d recommend this hotel as a lower-cost alternative for a pleasure stay in Las Vegas, and we commend the Golden Nugget for all they’re doing to keep the hotel fresh and the downtown casino environment alive.	
