Jul 19 2009 	No complaints here!	Just got back from several days in Vegas with the teens. Stayed one night at the Golden Nugget in the South tower to get a feel for downtown before moving to the Mandalay Bay. Check in was a breeze and in retrospect we should have been much more appreciative of not having to wait for elevators. (We had to wait in line for elevators at the Mandalay Bay!) Our adjoining rooms faced the parking garage, but who cares? The room was clean and comfortable and we got a good night's rest. We paid $52 per night (made the reservations the night before) and we got a coupon book that we used for half price breakfast and lunch buffets. The evening Fremont Experience was right outside our Casino door so we spent an hour or two there in the evening. The kids got to the pool at 10 AM when it opened and enjoyed the slide and sharks until check out time. No complaints here!	
Jul 18 2009 	MAY stay again	This was our second stay at the Nugget. First time 5 or 6 years ago was perfect in every way (except for the tight slots, which are even tighter now but hubby did fairly well on the blackjack tables). We've stayed at the Mirage as well as MGM. Arrived Sunday evening July 12 about 6 and faced a long line for check-in. Soon as we got to the desk we were told we should have gone to VIP check-in. DUH! I had forgotten that fact. We got 2 parlor suites, one for us, smoking, one for our couple friend, non-smoking. We were in the north tower, 2nd floor, friends on 6th floor. We had only a view of the concrete walls between buildings and rows of compressors. First negative was the smell. We've stayed in a lot of smoking rooms but none stunk as bad as this one. I brought my own expensive air freshener which didn't help at all. They should provide some type of decent ventilation. The bathroom fans did absolutely nothing when showering. Pictures online showed a bright cheery room, slightly feminine in decor but both of ours were done in very contemporary, dark tans and browns with minimal lighting and even with curtains opened, it felt like a cave. We had a non-working refrigerator which had 4 warm bottles of water. Maintenance came and inspected it and said they'd try to find a replacement. 10 min. later a tiny little elderly man who couldn't speak English showed up with a luggage rack carrying a really beat up replacement that was half the size of the one in the room. No way could he have lifted it, much less the broken one. We sent him away and soon another maintenance guy shows up and tries to work on it. He gave up after sparks shot out from the bottom and hit his boots! Next day 2 more guys show up with a working replacement.Another complaint was we killed 3 roaches in our room. Not a good sign. The small whirlpool tub had several long dark hairs in it and was so stained I couldn't tell if it was clean or not so only used the shower. I did go down to the VIP lounge to complain and she did offer to move us, but we declined as we were all settled in. She gave me a coupon book for our troubles. Oh boy! $5 discount off $65 Gordie Brown tickets, a free drink with purchase at several clubs and a couple of free desserts with purchase. As another reviewer mentioned, Gordie Brown was ok, but not worth the money. We did have 2 full bathrooms which was nice. Shampoo, conditioner, bar soap and body lotion was provided, no shower gel. We received 4 small bottles of water (complimentary) but they never supplied more. 2 large bottles of Figi water if you wanted to pay $4 each. The bed was very comfortable and was turned down our first nite but we put out the privacy tags after that since the rooms had already been cleaned each day and I'm never comfortable with people in our rooms when we are not there.The dinner buffet was mediocre. There were no cooked vegetable other than mashed potatoes and salads. No green beans, peas, corn, carrots, etc. I asked one of the servers and he said &quot;I'll go down to the warehouse and see what I can find&quot;. Of course, I already had my plate fixed. I went back to check about 10 minutes later and they had about a 3 serving platter with completely undercooked fresh green beans, red bell peppers and hard as a rock carrots. I guess since they were comped, we couldn't complain too much.My husband and our friends had breakfast (I slept in) at the buffet and said it was excellent. The first morning, we orderd room service and my Eggs Benedict were superb. We never ventured into the pool area although we had intended to. It was just too incredibly crowded with young children everywhere. If you do stay downtown (or just go there from the strip) be sure and catch Carl &quot;The Safe Sax&quot; Ferris. He is so great to watch. We've bought 2 of his CD's and they don't disappoint. He plays most nights and takes tips as well as selling his signed CD's.I would still recommend the Nugget hoping others would have the great experience we had the first time. But when making my reservations for our next stay, I will be very specific as to what I expect and will demand another room if it's anything like this last one. I suggest insisting on seeing the room before committing to accepting it.Oh, one other thing: Don't discount the slots at the airport. Our flight was delayed over 2 hours and my husband decided to try the one we'd seen a guy hit big on when we were there last year (stayed at MGM Grand). He ended up hitting a $600 jackpot (put $100 in) after 2 spins and 4 spins later, hit $2700. This was on a dollar machine. The gal that paid him said that was the best paying machine they had. Made the expense of the trip a little easier to swallow!!I would definitely take advantage of their online specials. We got the Parlor suites for $149.	
