Mar 24 2009 	Gold Club rooms overpriced for what you get...	My husband and I have visited Las Vegas many, many times. We have stayed at the Golden Nugget twice before, but this was our first stay in the Gold Club rooms. We enjoyed the VIP check-in, and the attendant at the counter was unfailingly polite and courteous. Our room was clean, and the bed was VERY comfy. There was a switch next to the bed that advertised as raising/lowering the window shade, but it was broken. Big flat-screen tv in the bedroom and a smaller one in the mirror in the bathroom were very nice touches, but the picture on the bigger one wasn't very good. No big deal. The bathroom set-up is nice with double sinks, and a vanity in the middle. Nice enclosed shower/tub with big shower head but the way it works is you have to get into the shower/tub to turn it on, so you've got water splashing on you before you're completely ready--design flaw to be sure! There is NO water pressure (my husband called the shower &quot;anemic&quot;) in either the shower or at the sinks. The closet, located in the bathroom, had spring-loaded doors that didn't stay open on their own, so you were constantly being whacked in the back or the arm while trying to get things hung or out of the closet. Definitely a negative. The dark colors in both the bedroom and the bathroom are beautiful, but after the initial oohs and aahs, were not welcoming.  There is no refrigerator or coffee maker in the room, which is a necessity for my husband. There is a coffee set-up in the elevator landing, but if you don't get there early, it's cold or gone. In the afternoon, the coffee set-up is replaced with waters, and snacks in large bowls. I believe this has been addressed several times in this forum--most people just dip their hands into the bowls and get their snacks, even though spoons and cups are provided. Oh, well... We used the hotel valet service several times during our 6-day stay at GN. Again, the staff was polite, but definitely overworked, as two or three attendants were tasked with retrieving cars for 20 or 30 guests in a 20-minute time frame. Due to immense construction being done at the GN, the entire top floor of their self-park garage is taken up with construction paraphernalia, so is unusable to hotel guests. Because of this, and the crowds for St. Patrick's Day, we were forced to use the valet, and even it was full.  The scale of construction at the GN is huge, with opening planned for sometime in 2009. Nowhere in the plans did I see arrangements for more parking, so this will become more of an issue as the construction nears completion and more people are using the already stretched-thin services. Please don't think our stay was bad--on the contrary, I would recommend the hotel. We had superb dinners at Vic and Anthony's Steakhouse and Red Sushi, located on the property. We wanted to use the pool, but it was completely FULL ALL THE TIME! All in all, it was a nice stay, but due to the crowds, it is my last stay downtown.	
