Jan 17 2009 	Efficient comfortable hotel	I spent six nights at the GN coinciding with CES. The hotel is expensively finished (marble floors in the public areas) and the room was pleasant and comfortable.Parking in the adjacent garage was free to residents and there were always free spaces.Because I was here on a working trip, I was getting to breakfast before seven. The staff was inflexible, not seating us in an empty cafe until additional servers started at 7 am. On several occasions service was very slow in the cafe.My room was nicely appointed and in good order. All the plumbing worked as expected and the supply of toiletries was good.The Starbucks on the south side opens at 5 am and the one in the casino is open 24/7, but that doesn't make up for the absence of a coffee maker in the room.The other downside was that guests tended to smoke around the lobby area and in the lifts, but that's a Vegas problem rather than specific to the GN.	
Jan 15 2009 	Rent a Car!	My wife and I just recently returned from the 2009 CES show (her company was presenting). The first night we stayed at Harrahs, which was more updated/modern hotel. And of course it's right in the middle of the action. The Golden Nugget was not updated, but I didn't mind--it had that old swanky charm to it. And it's in Downtown, I think not at all in walking distance.The Golden Nugget's main area's were updated and fancy enough, I loved the idea of the pool and the shark tank with the fish and sharks swimming by. You can see it from the lobby. Their buffet was closed, so we used the two-for-one coupon given at checkin for a main entree instead at the cafe. It was ok, just not as good a deal had it been the buffet.We're from Boston, and in my reading on Vegas nobody mentioned that there is PLENTY of FREE parking. Seriously. At least when we went. Every hotel has a self-park lot, which we were plenty happy with--let alone the valet service which we didn't even try. Some people complained about the Strip being a &quot;parking lot&quot;, but we didn't find it that bad at all (again, Boston). The reason I mention this is that the Golden Nugget is a long 3+ mi to the top of the Strip, which itself is 4 miles long. I wholeheartedly recommend getting a car to explore Vegas: save your energy for walking inside the huge resorts, rather than between them. The resorts themselves are so full of detail, you can easily get mentally and physically tuckered out. Perhaps at most you can do two a day (if looking at the architecture/sites is your thing). We had no problem getting from the middle of the Strip to Downtown where the Golden Nugget is by car. We had to return the car early, so a taxi from MGM Grand to GN was $25. Rent the car. We stayed here because at the time it had the lowest rate for the supposedly higher quality (hotwire &quot;4 star&quot; for $75 a night, during CES). I disagree with the stars (lower). But obviously if you can get a cheap room on the strip, do it. Otherwise, stay downtown if it's cheaper and rent a car, it's really not a problem at all, I found the size of Vegas to actually be more car friendly than walk friendly.	
