Dec 30 2008 	Christmas at the Golden Nugget - North Tower Room	My seventy-five year old mother and I stayed at the Golden Nugget for four nights starting on Wednesday, December 24th, 2008. We booked a North Tower room and when making our reservations online, we requested a room on the top floor, away from the elevator and the Fremont Street Experience, and we received a room on the tenth floor of the North Tower at the end of the hall overlooking the pool area. The North Tower is located just off from the hotel lobby and an easy walk to the main casino floor (as opposed to the South Tower).The large room included two queen-sized beds, each with three pillows on them, a clock radio, two comfy chairs beside a round table, one office-type chair with a table/desk, one regular chair next to the make-up table, a large HD television with about 20+ channels and a remote, and an iron/ironing board in the closet area, along with an extra pillow. We also found the doors slammed quite loudly, so we tried to close them as quietly as possible during our early morning gambling excursions.The medium-sized bathroom included three sets of towels, bottles of shampoo, conditioner and lotion, as well as a bar of facial soap and a bar of bath soap. There was a very nice handle in the shower, that my mother was able to use to get in and out of with ease.The parking garage is across from the hotel on First Street and was almost always full. If you are staying at the Golden Nugget, you will be issued a parking permit which you will show, along with your parking ticket, to exit.The casino is very large and crowded, with not much space to move around in. Despite staying four nights, my mother and I gambled elsewhere during our stay, as past visits to the Golden Nugget's casino resulted in empty pockets....The hotel is located in the Fremont Street Experience area, within walking distance of quite a few casinos. At night there is a light show, which is very entertaining.After taxes, the average rate per night for Room 1006 in the North Tower came to $79.37 U.S. Funds. We received a mailer from the hotel with this special rate, which was cheaper than the rate for the South Tower we had originally booked.Overall, we were very comfortable in the room as it was clean, but would probably stay in the South Tower next Christmas if the price for the North Tower jumps back to normal.	
Dec 30 2008 	Listen 	Read the other GN reviews, they are mostly good &amp; say all that needs to be said, about the fantastic stays to be had at the GN. At GN you get MORE than you pay for, what a bargain!Here are some LV/GN pointers:1. Get a rental car. The cost for a 3 day vacation is less than $20/ day (that is the cost of a ONE WAY trip to the strip) they provide maps for you, LV is not that difficult to drive around. It's WELL worth the cost. One more thing, get reservations at more than 1 rental car place (ie., Thrifty &amp; Dollar) for price comparison &amp; whichever line is shorter, use THAT reservation, the other you don't have to pay for (just forget about it). Taxi fare is NOT FAIR &amp; very expensive, don't pay them to drive you around!2. If you go Casino Hopping use Valet everywhere. There is NO Parking or Valet Fees, All you have to do is TIP the attendant a few bucks ($2-$3). The amount for 10 stops is still less than one round trip to &amp; from the strip. If your NOT a big spender don't worry about it, a few bucks is plenty. The valet guys appriciate any tip they get &amp; they get taken care of by the BIG tippers that come along frequently. They also are VERY willing to give any directions you might need to where ever you are going.3. I had well over an hour wait (close to 2 hrs) checking in at a hotel on the strip a few years ago &amp; learned my lesson. Ask for VIP/Diamond check in where ever you go. Most hotels offer this for a small fee, it's $20 at the GN. They have a separate check in &amp; lounge, for you to SIT &amp; wait, while drinking a beverage &amp; munching on a snack, IF there is anyone checking in ahead of you. The volume of this type of service is usually quite LOW, so if there are any mixups, the person helping you is NOT in a BAD mood (due to the stress of handling High volume business all day). They treat you like a VIP, instead of an average Joe (or Joan). This is a bargain as far as I'm concerned, $20 well spent (some places it's FREE, all you have to do is ask ahead of time!) This also helps check out, if the TV check out is not working, just drop off your key card here &amp; your DONE. 4. Bring your Swimwear! When the temp goes up in LV, there are only two places to be: inside gambling or outside in the pool! Most pools in LV are not just a Swim, they are an ADVENTURE, especially at GN!5. Make sure you TIP the dealers! There is nothing like sitting at a table, where the dealer is UPSET, because there is someone at the table REFUSING to tip the dealer! I was once at a table where a player won about a dozen hands &amp; did NOT tip the dealer a anything. The dealer was throwing cards almost OFF the table, the rest of the players were trying to HIDE &amp; the non-tipper did not have a clue that he was doing anything wrong, he just did not believe in sharing the wealth.	
Dec 30 2008 	Great for the Price	We just returned from a 4 night stay at the Golden Nugget. This was our 4th visit to the Nugget so we've witnessed the evolution of this property since it was purchased by Landry's.The improvements include a nicer, more comfortable casino with generally good drink service. The pool is awesome and the atmosphere in the common areas is much classier. However, service has suffered since the Nugget was owned by MGM. I remember during our 1st stay we were treated like royalty by everyone from the front desk clerks to the parking garage attendants. Our room was perfectly maintained by the housekeeping staff. The service has lost that personal touch. No one was rude - just not as friendly as in the past.We stayed in the south tower at an average rate of $54.00 a night. Don't get me wrong - for that price the room was good. It was just lacking a couple of simple things that could easily make it high class again. For instance, one night we had no wash cloths. Some of the towels were frayed around the edges. The sheets were too small for the bed to remain tucked in and the carpet in the halls was stained and worn.On the plus side, the beds have been upgraded to pillow top mattresses. The room had a flat screen TV with an impressive selection of channels for a casino hotel. The room was quiet although we did have a hard time regulating the temperature. It was cold outside but we still had to run the AC to be comfortable. The fan motor was pretty noisy and should probably be replaced. The next visit we'll probably upgrade to a North Tower room if it's not too much more expensive.We ate at the buffet on Christmas Day. It was nothing impressive - especially for $20.00 a person. The buffet at Main Street Station is much better and costs less. We also had breakfast at Carson Street Cafe and were pleased with the quality and the price.All in all, we had a good trip. The weather was unusually cold. Next time we'll visit in the summer so we can enjoy the pool.	
