Nov 21 2008 	Nugget is Nice...	I will start off by saying that this was my first time in Vegas, so I have nothing to compare the experience to. My employer paid for my flight and one night at the Golden Nugget as an incentive for winning a sales campaign. There were about 30 of us total that met there from around the West Coast. We arrived around 11:30 am and the check in line wasn’t too horribly long. However, when I finally arrived at the front desk, there appeared to be no reservation for my coworker and I. The Golden Nugget staff could not find my name or my coworker’s anywhere in the reservation database. I wasn’t too thrilled about this, as my employer said they had taken care of everything. Fortunately, there were extra rooms in the hotel, but we did have to charge it to our personal credit card until our district manager arrived later that day to work things out with the hotel. (I also noted that there was another couple next to us that was having difficulty checking in. They had a confirmation number, but apparently they weren’t in the system either. Hhhmm….) That aside, the Golden Nugget was quite nice. We were in the North Tower rooms. They were somewhat luxurious, but not spectacular. The view was of the parking lot. Oh well. My company did rent a Spa Suite to hold our awards ceremony. The Spa suite was amazing! It was two stories, had a great view, bar area, and just had a luxurious feel. I’m not sure how much they paid for that one. : ) The casino was quite nice and the dealers were pretty friendly. They talked and joked around with us, which was fun. One of them even remembered me when I came back later, even though I wasn’t a high roller or winner. The only place we ate there was the Carson Street Café. I wasn’t that impressed with the food, but they had $3 mimosas! The pool was absolutely amazing!!! I wanted to spend time there, but my coworkers wanted to see the Strip, and I didn’t want to hang out by myself, so the Strip it was! It became kind of expensive to take a taxi back and forth though. While, the Golden Nugget was nice, it doesn’t quite compare to the larger hotels like Caesar’s Palace, Bellagio, Treasure Island, etc. We walked through a few of them just to see what it was like, and I was quite impressed. If I return to Vegas (which I am still not sure that I will because I’m not a big gambler), I might consider a hotel on the Strip. I don’t know what the price difference is between the larger hotels and the Golden Nugget, but it might be worth it to be more centralized. Overall I enjoyed my stay. If you’re looking for something in the downtown Fremont area, then I would definitely recommend the Golden Nugget. But if you like the Strip, then I would say, stay on the Strip!	
