Nov 18 2008 	A Golden Stay at the Golden Nugget	This was our second trip to GN this year. We took the parents for their 40th wedding anniversary and we couldn't be happier with how things turned out.Upon arrival (10:00 am) we were greeted at the door by the bell persons. Figuring that we would have to wait for our rooms, we checked our luggage and proceeded to the check-in desk. What a delight to find that 1 of our rooms was ready to go. Our bags were taken to our room and within 15 minutes, we were out having fun.On the second day of our stay, the parents had some plumbing problems with their room. They were immediately upgraded to a suite and all their bags were moved for them. Great job GN!There was a problem with a room safe. One call to maintenance, and within 5 minutes, the problem was fixed.Our rooms were clean and bright. We were in the North tower, so we were only a short distance from the casino floor.With each of the minor things that happened, the GN staff responded with speed and congeniality. From the desk staff, to the casino host, the dealers in the casino to the bellpersons. Everyone we met was polite and went out of their way to help us.We ate at all of the restaurants at the GN. Each one was unique, and all were excellent!Comps were good. Final bill for our 3 night stay: $63.00 These were the tips from the meals we ate.Good job Golden Nugget. We will be back in April 2009!!!	
Nov 18 2008 	the only place to stay	We have been staying at the Nugget for 17 years (yes, I confess, we may have a gambling problem) and have watched it transform itself through several iterations. It was always a bargain, large rooms, clean, quiet, and good service. It has become a first class hotel, south tower rooms are always a steal, as low as 49 dollars in the winter. Although they do involve a walk to the casino proper and running the time share gauntlet (never make eye contact, never acknowledge their greeting, keep moving there is a Starbucks on the other side of the property), and check in can be a 30 minute wait (always send someone in your party to check and see if they south tower desk is open). The Gold Rooms expedite check in, the walk to the casino, and save you the time share panhandlers. Downtown is not for everyone, but this is the place to stay if you are staying downtown. Between Benions and the Nugget's poker rooms you will always find a game, Mama Cita's has great Mexican/Cuban (down by the El Cortez, never make the trek after sundown), and it is a bit lower key (but not too low, this is vegas).	
Nov 12 2008 	Super Spooky Halloween Experience (and not in a good way)	You know, I should expect issues any time I book and prepay through Expedia. I always have trouble in one way or another, and my recent visit to the Golden Nugget was no exception. I had planned the trip as a romantic getaway for my husband and myself, and requested a king bed in the newly-renovated North Tower. When we checked in (a process that took a long time, but it takes a long time everywhere in Las Vegas, honestly), we were told, of course, that we were in a room with two double beds. Not exactly the weekend I had imagined, as I'm not a Puritan. When I asked about a king bed, I was told that not a single king room was available in the entire hotel. I silently stared at the clerk for a while, and eventually she caved and &quot;consulted a manager&quot; who &quot;found&quot; a king room in the North Tower. Our room was a) behind the elevators, b) next to the ice machine, and c) directly across from the housekeeping phone. So it was quite possibly the worst room in the entire hotel, if not Las Vegas, which is what I get for being tough and demanding my way. Also, our view? A dirty wall. But we commenced with the power drinking, and eventually I forgot about how much the room location annoyed me. They do have awesome club sandwiches and divine breakfasts, so recovering the next day was rather nice in our noisy cave. Net net, it's expensive-ish for what you get, Fremont is nothing compared to the Strip (even on Halloween), and king beds are apparently as rare as big wins on their slot machines.	
Nov 12 2008 	Wonderful Stay at the Nugget!	My husband and I stayed at the GN the end of October. We had visited in August, but this was our first time staying downtown. We opted for the South Tower Rooms.We arrived at 11 am on a Saturday; no line at check-in whatsoever. The walk to/from the South Tower elevators was not bad aside from endless hounding of the timeshare people. There is also a Starbucks right next to elevators so that you can grab an early morning cup of coffee! The walk from the elevator to our room on the 20th floor was the longest. I suggest asking for a room closer to the elevators. View was not spectacular, but that was not a factor for us. Room was clean and beds very comfortable. Only real complaint about the room was that it was a bit dark, even with all lights on. We are not fancy eaters, so Carson Street Cafe worked just fine for us. Great food, reasonably priced, friendly staff. On a side note, although we did not make it there this trip, my husband loved Red Sushi Restaurant/Bar when we visited in August. Very friendly staff there, as well.The casino itself we found to be very nice. We both love Video Poker, so spent considerable amount of time playing at the 3 bars located throughout. Very friendly bartenders~don't forget to tip them WELL~they deserve it(they also make great Bloody Mary's)! Large selection of reel and video slots for the slot lovers! We thoroughly enjoyed our stay here. Super friendly staff and very clean from our room, to the casino, and restrooms. We look forward to booking our next trip here early 2009!	
