Nov 5 2008	Nugget was ok	I just returned from a stay at the Golden Nugget. While I have to agree with most of the reviews, as far as it being the nicest hotel downtown, I really dont think I would stay there again. I was with my elderly mother (in a wheelchair) and we stayed in the South tower. Check in took about 25 minutes at 3pm, and I asked specifically to be as close to the elevator as possible. On their online reservation form, there is also a place to put this request. While I know it was only a request, I was completely surprised to be almost as far away from the elevators as possible. We got off the elevator, went down a long hall, turned a corner, went down another long hall, and were at the end. I would have returned and asked for another room, but did not want to waste an hour trudging back down, waiting in line, etc. Other than that, every thing was fresh, clean and well maintained. The pool is a really nice amenity, although it does not get much sun during the day.I think next time I will pay less, and stay at one of the other hotels downtown, where the walk to the room does not take 20 minutes, even if they are not quite as up to date.	
Nov 3 2008 	2nd Stay at Nugget - Nice But To Much Noise	My boyfriend and I stayed at the Golden Nugget October 30 to November 2nd for Halloween and to celebrate my bf's birthday. This was our second time staying at the Nugget, but this time we didn't feel like splurging on the Gold Club rooms and only stayed in a regular South Tower room. I did ask nicely for a complimentary upgrade at check in, but since a manager was standing right there, we were only offered one for $25 a night, which we declined.As others have posted, the South Tower rooms really aren't that far away, and perfectly nice. We were on the 18th floor, in room 18109, which was a ways from the elevator, but had a nice view toward the strip and of the mountains in the distance. King size bed, flat screen TV, and nice and clean, a good value for three nights for $198.00 with our promo, including taxes. However, keep in mind that this hotel charges a $100 a night deposit at check in, and if you're using a debit card/check card, you still won't have signing privileges even with this deposit.This is by far the nicest hotel downtown, and seemed a bit less smokey than the rest as well. The pool area was very nice, with water slide, shark tank and hot tub. Personally, I thought the pool was a couple degrees to cold and the hot tub a couple degrees to warm, but still a nice place to get away and relax. It wasn't very crowded when we went, around 10:30am on a Friday morning, so we had no problem getting a chair and there was no line to go down the slide.The only real big complaint about the hotel was the noise. Between the rooms there is good insulation, we couldn't hear our neighbors, but they really need something around the doors to the hall. We could loudly hear the cleaning crew every morning, banging vacuums and talking on loud walkie talkies. In the middle of the night I could see a large slit of light on the sides and bottom of the door to the hall, so there is really no insulation on the door. Also, on Friday I was awoken promptly at 6am by a loud foghorn noise. I'm guessing this was to call the construction workers to work, since after that it was an incessant barrage of loud trucks backing up (that beep beep beep noise over and over) and lots of banging. I'd thought on the 18th floor we would be safe from the noise, but nope. We aren't that light of sleepers, so we ended up turning on the AC fan to try to drowned out the sound, it didn't block it out all the way, but was good enough to get back to sleep.Overall, I think we will stay here again if we want to hang out at Fremont Street, which is quite fun and cheap.	
